Step 1: Identify the Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities from the cash flow statement.  
• Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,504,752.68

Step 2: Identify the Total Current Liabilities from the balance sheet.  
• Accounts Payable = 3,350,120.00  
• Taxes Payable = 39,599.66  
• Total Current Liabilities = 3,350,120.00 + 39,599.66 = 3,389,719.66

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow Ratio using the formula:  
  Operating Cash Flow Ratio = (Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities) / (Total Current Liabilities)

Thus,  
  Operating Cash Flow Ratio = –4,504,752.68 / 3,389,719.66 ≈ –1.33

The result indicates that for every dollar of current liabilities, there is a negative operating cash flow of approximately 1.33 dollars.
